## Introduction:

*Italics will be editor comments, so the compiling of the project is easier.*

*Question of Interest: Are there any differences in obesity by age, gender, socio-economic status or lifestyle factors?*

This section explores obesity prevalence using data from the Scottish Health Survey (2013–2016). The response variable is obesity status (Yes/No). Differences in obesity prevalence are examined across age group, sex, employment status, and lifestyle factors such as fruit and vegetable intake. Approximately 30% of individuals in the dataset are classified as obese. The plots below compare obesity prevalence across these groups.

## Plots:

*The first set of code uses percentage to show the difference. I will also add an alt code for it to be shown on 0-1 scale, as proportions instead of percentages.*

```{r}
#| echo: FALSE
#| output: FALSE
library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)

data <- read.csv("DAProject3.csv", stringsAsFactors = TRUE)
```

```{r}
#| echo: FALSE
data$Obese <- factor(data$Obese)
```

#### Obesity vs Sex

```{r}
#| echo: false
data$Sex <- factor(data$Sex)
ggplot(data, aes(x = Sex, fill = Obese)) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  labs(
    x = "Sex",
    y = "Percentage"
  )

```

The percentage of individuals classified as obese is similar for males and females. Around 31% of females are classified as obese compared with about 29% of males. This suggests that the difference in obesity prevalence between the two groups is relatively small.

#### Obesity vs Age Group

```{r}
#| echo: false
data$AgeGroup <- factor(data$AgeGroup)
ggplot(data, aes(x = AgeGroup, fill = Obese)) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  labs(
    x = "Age Group",
    y = "Percentage"
  )
```

Clear differences in obesity prevalence can be observed across age groups. Approximately 16% of individuals aged 16–24 are classified as obese, and this increases steadily across older age groups. The highest prevalence appears in the 65–74 age group at around 36–37%. The prevalence then decreases slightly to about 29% in the 75+ group.

#### Obesity vs Employment

```{r}
#| echo: false
data$Employment <- factor(data$Employment)
ggplot(data, aes(x = Employment, fill = Obese)) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  labs(
    title = "Obesity vs Employment",
    x = "Employment",
    y = "Percentage"
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  coord_flip()
```

Differences in obesity prevalence are visible across employment categories. Individuals permanently unable to work show the highest obesity prevalence at roughly 42–43%. Those looking after home or family also have relatively high obesity levels at around 37%. In contrast, individuals in full-time education have the lowest prevalence at approximately 17%.

#### Obesity vs Fruit Intake

```{r}
#| echo: false
data$Fruit <- factor(data$Fruit)
ggplot(data, aes(x = Fruit, fill = Obese)) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  labs(
    x = "Fruit Intake",
    y = "Percentage"
  )
```

The percentage of obesity is very similar between individuals who meet the recommended fruit intake and those who do not. Both groups show obesity levels of around 30%. This suggests that fruit intake alone does not show a strong difference in obesity prevalence in this dataset.

#### Obesity vs Vegetable Intake

```{r}
#| echo: false
data$Veg <- factor(data$Veg)
ggplot(data, aes(x = Veg, fill = Obese)) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  labs(
    x = "Vegetable Intake",
    y = "Percentage"
  )
```

A similar pattern is observed for vegetable intake. Individuals who meet the recommended vegetable intake show obesity prevalence of around 30%, while those who do not are slightly higher at around 33%. However, the difference between the groups remains relatively small.

